-- PRESS DIGEST - RUSSIA - Oct 8
-- 
-- Wed Oct 08, 2014 05:56AM EDT
-- None



MOSCOW, Oct 8 (Reuters) - The following are some of the stories in Russia's newspapers on Wednesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

VEDOMOSTI www.vedomosti.ru - Russia's retailers say food imports have shifted towards deliveries from Belarus, the daily says, in connection with a fall in dairy product imports from the EU, Canada, Australia, the United States and Norway by more than 75 percent in September. - The government has decided to reduce its contribution to the construction of a new Black Sea port of Taman - aimed at easing logistics constraints at Novorosiisk port - by 26 billion roubles ($650.08 million) to 202 billion roubles($5.05 billion) according to transport ministry.- Agricultural Bank of China is opening a subsidiary in Russia, which will make it China's fourth lender opening business in Russia, hit by EU and U.S. sanctions. KOMMERSANT www.kommersant.ru - The finance ministry is looking to attract Russia's telecom companies MTS, MegaFon, Vimpelcom and Rostelecom, as well as state holding Rostec, to take part in investing in the national global navigation system GLONASS, after having already spent over 4 billion roubles on the project, the daily reports. - Russians withdrew more than 34 billion roubles ($850.11 million) from their accounts in state lender Sberbank <SBER.MM> in September after the rouble weakened recently. - Russia's natural gas monopoly Gazprom <GAZP.MM> could review its strategy in Europe and might shy away from earlier plans to acquire assets in some European gas retailers, the daily said referring to Gazprom CEO Alexei Miller. - Crimean authorities are offering to help Ukrainian tycoon Dmitry Firtash find an investor to buy his titanium operations there, which are the biggest producer of titanium dioxide in Eastern Europe. Firtash dismisses allegations he intends to sell his business in Crimea. ROSSIISKAYA GAZETA www.rg.ru - Police have filed its first criminal case against a Russian citizen fighting in Ukraine against pro-Russian rebels. Muscovite Roman Zheleznov might be charged for taking part in an armed conflict abroad for profit and could face up to 7 years in prison even if his " hands are not stained with blood", the daily says.  NEZAVISISMAYA GAZETA www.ng.ru - Crimean police have been conducting raids against local religious activists in the region after several independent sources reported that Ukraine could take advantage of a ceasefire in the East and provoke unrest on the peninsular with the help of Islamic radicals, the daily says. - Russia's lawmakers could consider introduction of a four-days working week as a measure to ease social tensions during the possible economic crisis, the daily says.